edu.caltech.nanodb.storage

Class DBFileReader

  • java.lang.Object
    • edu.caltech.nanodb.storage.DBFileReader
  • Direct Known Subclasses:
    DBFileWriter

    public class DBFileReader
extends Object

    This class provides the basic abilty to read a DBFile as a single sequential file, ignoring the fact that it is actually broken into pages. As the file-pointer moves through the file, the Storage Manager is used to load individual pages into the buffer manager.

    It is certainly possible that a value being read might span two adjacent data pages. In these cases, the read will be a little slower, as the reader must read partial data from the first page, and then load and read the remainder of the data from the next page.

    There is a subclass of this reader, the DBFileWriter, which allows data to be read and written sequentially to a DBFile. This is mainly provided to support write-ahead logging, which is generally a very sequential operation.

      • checkDBPage

        protected void checkDBPage()
                    throws IOException
        This helper function checks to see whether the currently cached DBPage object matches the page-number of the current position value. If they don't match, or if there currently isn't any DBPage cached, then this method will load the required DBPage from the Storage Manager.
        Throws:
        IOException - if an IO error occurs while reading the required database page

      • releasePage

        public void releasePage()
        This method causes the writer to set the current DBPage to null, so that the reader doesn't hold on to a page that might need to be flushed out of the buffer manager.
        To Do:
        Once we have page-pinning, this will also need to unpin the page.

      • readVarString255

        public String readVarString255()
                        throws IOException
        This method reads and returns a variable-length string whose maximum length is 255 bytes. The string is expected to be in US-ASCII encoding, so multibyte characters are not supported.

        The string's data format is expected to be a single unsigned byte b specifying the string's length, followed by b more bytes consisting of the string value itself.

        Throws:
        IOException

      • readVarString65535

        public String readVarString65535()
                          throws IOException
        This method reads and returns a variable-length string whose maximum length is 65535 bytes. The string is expected to be in US-ASCII encoding, so multibyte characters are not supported.

        The string's data format is expected to be a single unsigned short (two bytes) s specifying the string's length, followed by s more bytes consisting of the string value itself.

        Throws:
        IOException
